The following module uses FOUR different functions that all cause atom-table exhaustion on user input:

```elixir
defmodule MyApp.DynamicDispatch do
  def by_name(req), do: String.to_atom(req["name"])
  def by_chars(req), do: List.to_atom(String.to_charlist(req["name"]))
  def by_bin(req), do: :erlang.binary_to_atom(req["name"], :utf8)
  def by_module(req), do: Module.concat([MyApp.Plugins, req["name"]])
end
```

Many linters only catch `String.to_atom/1`. Produce a fixed module that uses an explicit string->term mapping for all four functions. Every function must return a fixed value (atom, module, or `{:error, :unknown}`) drawn from a compile-time allowlist. Do not rely on `String.to_existing_atom/1` (still a trap if the atom table is seeded from user data). Write the fix to `lib/my_app/dynamic_dispatch.ex`.
